 Pathology in Merleau-Ponty takes up Merleau-Ponty’s phenomenology of the body to explore the ideas of normality, abnormality, and pathology. Focusing on the lived experiences of various styles of embodiment, the book challenges our usual conceptions of normality and abnormality and shows how seemingly objective scientific research, such as the study of pathological symptoms, is inadequate to the phenomena it purports to comprehend. The book offers new insights into our understandings of health and illness, ability and disability, and the scientific and cultural practices that both enable and limit our capacity for diverse experiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aEpidemiologyxPhilosophy. 0aPublic healthxPhilosophy. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPsychology : Psychology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aBlair, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, Jennifer E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBredlau, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBredlau, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDeroo, Neal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowell, Whitney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Gabrielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRakoczi, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReynolds, Joel Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlatman, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVenable, Hannah Lyn, econtr